# Cursor Rules

## Versioning
Increment `package.json` version with every push to `main`. Feature branches: one bump before merge.

## Commit Messages
Conventional commits, one line, imperative mood:
- feat: add new feature
- fix: resolve bug
- chore: maintenance task
- docs: update documentation
- refactor: restructure code

## Code Principles
1. No nesting — use early returns
2. Simple > clever — optimize for readability
3. Small functions — single purpose
4. Delete dead code — no unused imports/vars
5. No magic values in rules — use named constants in rules.js
6. TypeScript only — no .js/.jsx in application code
7. Turbopack — use --turbopack for Next.js dev and build
8. Latest stable — stay current with Next.js, React, dependencies
9. Skeleton loading — every async boundary needs a loading state
10. Prettier handles formatting — never add @stylistic/* formatting rules

## Prettier/@stylistic Boundary
Prettier handles ALL formatting via `prettier/prettier: error`. The @stylistic plugin is only for blank-line structure rules (lines-around-comment, lines-between-class-members). Never add @stylistic spacing, indent, quotes, or bracket rules.

## File Roles
rules.js       → Rule groups (prettier, jsDoc, stylisticTs, tsEslint); export merged rules
utils.js       → getTsConfigFile, debug; Node-only, no undef disable
eslint.config.js → Flat config; plugins, globals (module, process, require), rules
docs/          → ESLINT-AUDIT, ESLINT-STANDARDS, AI-CODE-STANDARDS

## Verification
npm run lint   — ESLint
npm run build  — compile to dist/
npm test       — Vitest + lint
